answers.body_markdown:
There&#39;s no `null` in Rust (and no Null Pointer Exception, Rust is designed for safety).

You must either

**1)** use an [option][1] (i.e. a field of type `Option&lt;TcpStream&gt;`)

**2)** or better: return a [result][2] when building the struct

Here, the best option would probably be to connect from inside a function returning a `Result&lt;FistClient&gt;`, so that you don&#39;t have to check whether your struct has a valid stream.

I would do something like this:

```
pub struct FistClient {
    addr: String,
    conn: TcpStream,
}

impl FistClient {
    pub fn new(ip: &amp;str, port: &amp;str) -&gt; Result&lt;Self&gt; {
        Ok(FistClient {
        	addr: format!(&quot;{}:{}&quot;, ip, port),
		    conn: TcpStream::connect(&amp;self.addr)?,
        })
    }
}
```
 
Side note: It&#39;s really preferable to not build your applications with calls to `panic`, even when you think you&#39;re just building a dirty draft. [Handle errors][3] instead.


  [1]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/option/
  [2]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/result/
  [3]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch09-00-error-handling.html

In Rust, the idea of `null` is modelled with `Option`. You give a field the type `Option&lt;TcpStream&gt;` to indicate that it might not be there (`None`), or be a valid value (`Some(TcpStream)`).

```
pub struct FistClient {
    addr: String,
    conn: Option&lt;TcpStream&gt;,
}

impl FistClient {
    pub fn new(ip: &amp;str, port: &amp;str) -&gt; Self {
        FistClient {
            addr: String::from(ip) + &quot;:&quot; + &amp;String::from(port),
            conn: None,
        }
    }

    pub fn connect(&amp;mut self, ip: &amp;str, port: &amp;str) {
        let res = TcpStream::connect(&amp;self.addr);
        match res {
            Ok(c) =&gt; self.conn = Some(c),
            Err(_) =&gt; panic!(),
        }
    }
}
```

