Yes, you can use mapped types to do this, ever since TypeScript 3.1 introduced  [the ability to map tuple/array types](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/wiki/What&#39;s-new-in-TypeScript#mapped-types-on-tuples-and-arrays).  You could either do it the &quot;forward&quot; way, like you were doing:

    function UnWrap&lt;T extends Array&lt;Wrap&lt;One | Two | Three&gt;&gt;&gt;(...args: T) {
      return args.map(i =&gt; i.obj) as {
        [K in keyof T]: T[K] extends Wrap&lt;infer U&gt; ? U : never
      };
    }
    
    let res2 = UnWrap(one, two, three, two); // [One, Two, Three, Two]
    
or the &quot;reverse&quot; way, using [inference from mapped types](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/advanced-types.html#inference-from-mapped-types):

    function UnWrap2&lt;T extends Array&lt;One | Two | Three&gt;&gt;(
      ...args: { [K in keyof T]: Wrap&lt;T[K]&gt; }
    ) {
      return args.map(i =&gt; i.obj) as T;
    }
    let res3 = UnWrap2(one, two, three, two); // [One, Two, Three, Two]

Either way will work, as you can see... and either way, the compiler won&#39;t be able to understand that `args.map(i =&gt; i.obj)` performs the type manipulation you&#39;re doing, so you&#39;ll need to use a [type assertion](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/basic-types.html#type-assertions) or the equivalent of one (such as using a single [overload](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/functions.html#overloads) signature).

Okay, hope that helps.  Good luck!

